Covid-19 Dataset

Introduction

This analysis explores the Covid-19 infection statistics of South Korea in the first half of 2020. The aim of this analysis is to get insights into the main factors causing the spread and mortality of the infection and generating guidelines on how to deal with respiratory virus pandemics in the future.

Preparation and overview

Loading and cleaning

Putting the data from separate in .csv files into a dictionary of pandas dataframes

Show the code 
data_files = csv_files = [f for f in os.listdir("data") if f.endswith(".csv")]
data = {}
for file in csv_files:
    file_path = os.path.join("data/", file)
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
    data[file[:-4]] = df

Loading 2010 population data summary from Korean Statistical Information Service for reference:

Show the code 
population_data = pd.read_csv("data/census_population.csv")
population_data = population_data.iloc[2:20]
population_data = population_data[["By age ", "2010"]].reset_index(drop=True)
population_data["2010"] = pd.to_numeric(population_data["2010"])
population_data = population_data.groupby(population_data.index // 2).sum(
    numeric_only=False
)
for i in population_data.index:
    population_data.iloc[i, 0] = str(i) + ("0s")
population_data.iloc[0, 0] = population_data.iloc[0, 0][1:]

The data consists of:

  1. Case Data Case: Data of COVID-19 infection cases in South Korea
  2. Patient Data PatientInfo: Epidemiological data of COVID-19 patients in South Korea PatientRoute: Route data of COVID-19 patients in South Korea (currently unavailable)
  3. Time Series Data Time: Time series data of COVID-19 status in South Korea TimeAge: Time series data of COVID-19 status in terms of the age in South Korea TimeGender: Time series data of COVID-19 status in terms of gender in South Korea TimeProvince: Time series data of COVID-19 status in terms of the Province in South Korea
  4. Additional Data Region: Location and statistical data of the regions in South Korea Weather: Data of the weather in the regions of South Korea SearchTrend: Trend data of the keywords searched in NAVER which is one of the largest portals in South Korea SeoulFloating: Data of floating population in Seoul, South Korea (from SK Telecom Big Data Hub) Policy: Data of the government policy for COVID-19 in South Korea

time_data["new_cases"] = time_data["confirmed"] - time_data["confirmed"].shift(1)

Weekly aggregations and additional data manipulation

Country:

Show the code 
# Aggregating the day to day data into weeks by taking the last data point of the week
weekly_time = time_data.resample("W").last()

# Weekly new cases
weekly_time["new_cases"] = weekly_time["confirmed"] - weekly_time["confirmed"].shift(
    1
).fillna(0)

# Weekly tests done
weekly_time["weekly_tested"] = weekly_time["test"] - weekly_time["test"].shift(
    1
).fillna(0)

# Percentage of positive tests
weekly_time["positivity"] = (
    weekly_time["new_cases"] / weekly_time["weekly_tested"] * 100
)

Province:

Show the code 
# Aggregating the day to day data into weeks by taking the last data point of the week
weekly_time_province = data["TimeProvince"].groupby("province").resample("W").last()

# Weekly new cases
weekly_time_province["new_cases"] = np.NaN
for province in weekly_time_province["province"]:
    weekly_time_province.loc[
        weekly_time_province["province"] == province, "new_cases"
    ] = weekly_time_province.loc[
        weekly_time_province["province"] == province, "confirmed"
    ] - weekly_time_province.loc[
        weekly_time_province["province"] == province, "confirmed"
    ].shift(
        1
    ).fillna(
        0
    )
weekly_time_province = weekly_time_province.droplevel("province")

Additional calculations

Creating a two day doubling line for Figure 3:

Show the code 
# Creating an array of dates starting from the start date
dates = pd.date_range(start="2020-01-20", end="2020-06-30", freq="2D")

# Creating an array of confirmed cases that doubles every two days
confirmed_cases = np.power(2, np.arange(len(dates) // 2 + 1))
confirmed_cases = np.tile(confirmed_cases, 2)[: len(dates)]

# Creating an array of new cases for each date
new_cases = np.zeros(len(dates))
new_cases[0] = confirmed_cases[0]
# Creating a DataFrame with the date, confirmed, and new cases columns
doubling_line = pd.DataFrame({"date": dates, "confirmed": confirmed_cases})
doubling_line["new_cases"] = doubling_line["confirmed"] - doubling_line[
    "confirmed"
].shift(1).fillna(0)

Timeline overview of total infections

As an introduction to the situation I begin this analysis with a overview of country wide pandemic timeline and policy overview.

Policy overview and the new cases timeline

The first infection COVID-19 infection case in South Korea was confirmed in January 20th 2020. This resulted in the South Korean government raising the infectious disease alert from level one (blue) to level two (yellow), but since it was only one case no other measures were taken. The new cases timeline can be viewed in Figure 1. The inflection points of the rate of the spread can sometimes be more easily pinpointed by plotting the number of new cases over total cases, the result is in Figure 3.

February policies

At the end of January and the first half of February there were several new confirmed cases every week. During this time period the governmental concern grew and several policies were put in place, the list can be found in Table 1.

The most important implemented policies that were:

  • Special immigration procedures for visitors from China, Macau and Hong Kong. These included visa free entry suspension, quarantine and testing procedures.
  • Authorization of diagnostic kits from two manufacturers alongside a release of a self-diagnosis app.
  • The infectious Disease Alert was raised by two levels orange (2020-01-28) and red (2020-02-23). These levels allowed the government to take special measures. At the orange level more rigorous testing was begun alongside issuing of masks and recommendations for schools. At level red the size of social gathering was limited. Contacts were traced and exposed individuals were isolated.

“These measures increased the rates of testing, as can be seen by the number of weekly tests performed displayed in Figure 1. As a result, the number of new cases started to sharply increase. The search trend data in Figure 2 shows that the public was already aware of the coronavirus after the blue and yellow alertness levels were raised; therefore, the increase in testing is mostly due to the availability of tests and not additional social awareness.

The surge in tests also coincided with the surge in confirmed cases, which means that it is possible that a large number of cases were not diagnosed prior to the implementation of the package of policies.”

March policies

The number of new cases increased sharply until a major inflection point that began in 2020-03-01. The list of policies during this period can be seen in Table 2.

During this period several important policies were implemented:

  • A national social distancing campaign was launched that issued guidelines on social distancing on 2020-02-29 that included working from home, wearing masks, staying at home as much as possible.
  • Daycare centers were closed.
  • Schools were not opened on March (in South Korea March is the beginning of a semester after a winter break Dec-Feb).
  • Special immigrations procedures were implemented for visitors from largest outbreak countries.
  • Drive-trough screening centers were opened.

These measures, severely restricted social contacts as the social distancing campaign limited most of everyday meeting places. After the implementation of these measures a sharp decrease in new cases was observed as seen in Figure 1.

Another sharp decline in cases can be seen starting with 2020-04-05. A list of policies preceding this decline can be seen in Table 3.

May policies

The number of new cases bottomed in the week ending in 2020-05-03 and then started to increase raising nearly five times over the following month. The policies after which the increase followed can be found in Table 4.

32 Social Social Distancing Campaign Weak(1st) 2020-05-06 nan
54 Administrative Close bars and clubs administrative order to close bars and clubs 2020-05-08 2020-06-07

The South Korean government loosened the social distancing policies on May 6th, according to chatGPT these changes included: 1. Easing of social distancing guidelines: South Korea relaxed some of its social distancing guidelines in certain areas that were considered low-risk for COVID-19 transmission. This allowed some businesses, including libraries, museums, and art galleries, to reopen under certain conditions.

  1. Sports events and religious services: The government allowed professional sports to resume without spectators, and religious services were permitted to resume under certain conditions, such as limiting the number of attendees.

  2. Schools reopening: South Korea also began a phased reopening of schools, starting with high school seniors, middle school students, and first and second graders. Other grades were set to follow in the coming weeks.

Policy section overview

Due to the nonuniform nature of policy data, this section mostly relies on observational evidence that attempts to correlate the inflection points in the COVID-19 infection spread with governmental policies, based on timestamps. This observational evidence suggests that the most effective social policies were those related to social distancing and limiting the number of contacts that the population has. Most notably, the social distancing campaign in early March correlated with the cessation of the exponential rise in new COVID-19 cases. As South Korea had a better situation than most countries in that region, the mandatory 14-day quarantine in April also correlated with a decrease in new cases. The social distancing policy was eased up at the beginning of May, which correlated with a triple increase in weekly new cases, but this trend was reversed as the social distancing rules were made stricter again. These observational correlations strongly suggest the effectiveness of social distancing policies in halting the spread of respiratory infections.

Weather data

Respiratory infections are often related to weather conditions. The data sets provides a number of meterological parameters. Yet the literature shows that the temperature alone is the best predictor of respiratory infections (Falagas et al. (2008), Carder et al. (2005)) therefore in order to compare the weather conditions with the timeline of South Korean covid-19 situation I’ve aggregated the dataset into weekly averages of temperature across the country. The resulting comparison can be seen in Figure 4. The temperature does not differ throughout the region drastically during this timeline, as seen in Table 6, therefore a average of temperature was used for this figure.

The temperature mostly increased over the observed period. To investigate the correlation between new cases, temperature and temperature 5 days prior since the relation between temperature and respiratory infection cases usually have a lag effect (Falagas et al. (2008)). The 5 day lag time is also confirmed by the patient data in Patient data overview.

Calculating the correlation troughout the range:

Show the code 
# Merging new cases and temperature into a single table
daily_temp_cases = pd.merge(
    time_data["new_cases"],
    daily_temp,
    left_index=True,
    right_index=True,
    how="outer",
)
# 5 day lag column
daily_temp_cases["avg_temp_5day_prior"] = daily_temp_cases["avg_temp"].shift(5)

daily_temp_cases.dropna(how="any", inplace=True)
get_correlation_pairs(daily_temp_cases, negative_cut_off=-0.1)
r-value feature_pair
0 -0.244 (new_cases, avg_temp)
1 -0.23 (new_cases, avg_temp_5day_prior)

There is a slight negative correlation between both current and 7-day prior temperature. To see the range of the correlation we can check for correlations by dates up to the peak of March 8th:

Show the code

And after:

Show the code 
get_correlation_pairs(daily_temp_cases["2020-03-08":], negative_cut_off=-0.1)
r-value feature_pair

1 -0.422 (new_cases, avg_temp_5day_prior)

Weather data summary

According to the data, there is a significant correlation between the number of new COVID-19 cases and the temperature 5 days prior, particularly after the peak when the number of cases began to decline. Most regions in the northern hemisphere with a seasonal climate showed a significant negative correlation between new COVID-19 cases and temperature (McClymont and Hu (2021)). This suggests that warmer weather may have had an additional beneficial effect in reducing the number of new COVID-19 cases. While humidity and wind speed may also have significant effects, the results in the literature are more ambiguous, so this analysis did not include them.

Case map

It is interesting to see the location and magnitude of these cases on a map. The Case data also includes coordinates of some of the cases, yet for others only city or province name is provided. In order to fill in the missing values the coordinates were gathered from a geocoding service geocode.maps.co . This was done by making a request to the service by inputting the available case information that could pin point the location, that is city, province, and case information. Here is the code:

Mortality prediction

The features in the patient data set allows us to make statistical insights in which patients are more likely to die from the infection.

The overall mortality rate is:

Show the code 
round(
    len(patient_info.loc[patient_info["state"] == "deceased"])
    / len(patient_info)
    * 100,
    2,
)
1.51

Mortality machine learning prediction model

In order to asses the patient characteristics associated with mortality this analysis uses a machine learning algorithm to fit a logistic regression model. The features were chosen manually by selecting those characteristics that could have explainable impacts on mortality. The features were sex, age and province.

Data preparation:

Show the code 
# Making the state value binary
patient_info.loc[patient_info["state"] != "deceased", "state"] = "alive"
# Making a copy of the data set to be used for this ML fitting
patient_ml_set = patient_info[["age_numeric", "sex", "province", "state"]].copy()
# dropping rows with any of the selected feature values missing
patient_ml_set = patient_ml_set.dropna(how="any")
# Setting binary values to non numeric features
patient_ml_set = pd.get_dummies(patient_ml_set, columns=["province", "sex"])
# Loading the model
le = LabelEncoder()
# Transforming the result feature
patient_ml_set["state"] = le.fit_transform(patient_ml_set["state"])
# Splitting the data set into a 70% training set and a 30% test set
train_patient, test_patient = train_test_split(
    patient_ml_set,
    test_size=0.3,
    random_state=1,
)

Model training and prediction:

Show the code 
patient_mortality_model = LogisticRegression(solver="lbfgs", max_iter=10000)
patient_mortality_model.fit(train_patient.drop("state", axis=1), train_patient["state"])
patient_prediction = patient_mortality_model.predict(test_patient.drop("state", axis=1))

Correctly predicted positives:

While the model demonstrates reasonable accuracy and precision, its recall score and therefore F1 score are notably poor. This suggests that the model is failing to identify most of the positive outcomes, although it is correctly avoiding false positives. This poor performance is likely due to the low number of positive results in the dataset. While the model’s metrics may not be strong enough for predictive purposes, it is worth noting that its accuracy and precision scores are above random. As such, the patterns learned by the model may still be useful for analyzing patient data.

Sex significance test

Although the higher mortality with age is logical, the significantly higher mortality in males is not obvious, therefore to test this phenomena a statistic chi square test is implemented in the analysis.

Preparing the dataset:

Show the code 
patient_sex_mortality_df = patient_info[["sex", "age_numeric", "province", "state"]]
patient_sex_mortality_df = patient_sex_mortality_df.dropna(how="any")
# Dropping 100s age group for low n
patient_sex_mortality_df = patient_sex_mortality_df[
    patient_sex_mortality_df["age_numeric"] != 100
].reset_index(drop=True)

Getting a sample with equal number of males and females in each age group:

Show the code 
# Counting the number of males and females in each age group
age_sex_group_counts = patient_sex_mortality_df.groupby(["age_numeric", "sex"]).count()
# Getting the minimal value in each age group
age_sex_group_counts = age_sex_group_counts.groupby("age_numeric").min()["state"]
# Empty sample dataframe
age_sex_sample = pd.DataFrame(columns=patient_sex_mortality_df.columns)
# Making a sample dataset with equal males and females in each age group
for age in patient_sex_mortality_df["age_numeric"].unique():
    sample_male = (
        patient_sex_mortality_df.groupby(["age_numeric", "sex"])
        .get_group((age, "male"))
        .sample(age_sex_group_counts[age], random_state=31)
    )
    sample_female = (
        patient_sex_mortality_df.groupby(["age_numeric", "sex"])
        .get_group((age, "female"))
        .sample(age_sex_group_counts[age], random_state=31)
    )
    age_sex_sample = pd.concat(
        [age_sex_sample, sample_male, sample_female], ignore_index=True
    )

age_sex_sample[["age_numeric", "sex"]].groupby("age_numeric").value_counts()

Calculating a chi-square test statistic:

Show the code 
# Creating a contingency table
sex_mortality_con_table = pd.crosstab(age_sex_sample["sex"], age_sex_sample["state"])
# Calculating the chisquare statistics
sex_mortality_con_table_stats = chi2_contingency(sex_mortality_con_table)
print("Chi-square test statistic:", round(sex_mortality_con_table_stats[0], 2))
print("p-value:", round(sex_mortality_con_table_stats[1], 5))
Chi-square test statistic: 15.04
p-value: 0.00011

The Chi-square test results show that indeed males have a significantly higher mortality rate on a sample that had equal number of males and females in each age group.

)

fig_mortality_coeff.show()

The mortality was highest in the Daegu province and lowest in Gyeonggi-do. Daegu had the highest spike in infections and this likely caused the high mortality rate, yet it is still worth investigating wether other factors had influence.

The province data has some characteristics of each province, therefore we can correlate these features to the mortality coefficients.

Daegu province mortality significance

To test the hypothesis that Daegu province has a significantly higher mortality, this analysis employs the chi-square statistic test.

Taking a sample with equal number of people from Daegu and not in each age and sex group:

Show the code 
province_sample_data = patient_sex_mortality_df.copy()
province_sample_data["province"] = province_sample_data["province"].apply(
    lambda x: "Daegu" if x == "Daegu" else "not_daegu"
)
province_group_counts = province_sample_data.groupby(
    ["sex", "province", "age_numeric"]
).count()
province_group_counts = province_group_counts.groupby(
    ["age_numeric", "sex", "province"]
).min()["state"]
province_group_counts

province_sample = pd.DataFrame(columns=province_sample_data.columns)

for age in province_sample_data["age_numeric"].unique():
    for province in province_sample_data["province"].unique():
        # Select male and female patients in the current age group and province
        male_patients = province_sample_data[
            (province_sample_data["age_numeric"] == age)
            & (province_sample_data["sex"] == "male")
            & (province_sample_data["province"] == province)
        ]
        female_patients = province_sample_data[
            (province_sample_data["age_numeric"] == age)
            & (province_sample_data["sex"] == "female")
            & (province_sample_data["province"] == province)
        ]

        # Sample an equal number of males and females in the current age group and province
        male_sample = male_patients.sample(
            province_group_counts[(age, "male")].min(), random_state=31
        )
        female_sample = female_patients.sample(
            province_group_counts[(age, "female")].min(), random_state=31
        )
        province_sample = pd.concat(
            [province_sample, male_sample, female_sample], ignore_index=True
        )

province_sample.drop("state", axis=1).value_counts().to_frame().head(10)

Daeugo chi square significance test:

Show the code 
# Creating a contingency table
province_mortality_con_table = pd.crosstab(
    province_sample["province"], province_sample["state"]
)
# Calculating the chisquare statistics
province_mortality_chi_stats = chi2_contingency(province_mortality_con_table)

print("p-value:", round(province_mortality_chi_stats[1], 5))

The results show that Daegu province has a significantly higher mortality than the rest of the provinces.

Contact number analysis

The patient data includes information on the number of contacts that some patients had, as well as the ID of the patient who infected them in certain cases. This allows us to investigate the transmission of the infection from one person to another.

Checking wether particular age groups tend to have more contacts:

Show the code 
age_contacts = (
    patient_info[["age", "contact_number"]]
    .groupby("age")
    .agg({"contact_number": "median"})
    .T
)

The median contact numbers of the age groups do not differ significantly, but it tends to be higher in the 40s age group. The high number in the 90s age group is due to a small sample size.

Checking which age group infected the most patients:

Show the code 
contacts = (
    patient_info[["age", "infected_by"]]
    .groupby("age")
    .value_counts()
    .to_frame()
    .reset_index()
)
contacts = contacts.rename({0: "count"}, axis=1)
contacts["infected_by"] = contacts["infected_by"].astype(str)
patient_info["patient_id"] = patient_info["patient_id"].astype(str)
contacts = contacts.merge(
    patient_info[["age", "patient_id"]],
    left_on="infected_by",
    right_on="patient_id",
    how="left",
    suffixes=("", "_infector"),
)

Knowing the infected population age distribution, displayed in Figure 8. People in their 40s have infected a disproportionally high number of patients in regards of the total number of patients in this age group.

Further, it is interesting to see which age groups infected which the most.

Calculating the contacts by age groups and making a pivot table:

Show the code 
contacts_aggregated = contacts.groupby(["age", "age_infector"]).sum(numeric_only=True)
contacts_aggregated = contacts_aggregated.reset_index()
contacts_pivot = contacts_aggregated.pivot_table(
    index="age_infector", columns="age", values="count", aggfunc="sum"
)

fig_contacts_heatmap = px.imshow(contacts_pivot, width=base_fig_wid * dpi)

fig_contacts_heatmap.update_xaxes(title="Patient Age")
fig_contacts_heatmap.show()

As can be seen from the heatmap in Figure 10, age groups mostly tend to spread the infection among themselves. There is also a notable number of cases where people in their 20s infected people in their 50s and vice versa, similarly people in their 30s infected people in their 60s and vice versa, this is most likely due to children visiting their parents.

Discussion and Result Summary

The timeline of results indicates that the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases began to increase exponentially only after the emergency approval of COVID-19 test kits. This suggests that undiagnosed infections could have played a significant role in the uncontrolled spread of the virus.

The timeline of confirmed COVID-19 cases also revealed that the exponential increase in cases began to slow down and eventually decrease after the implementation of strict social distancing policies. However, the number of cases started to increase again when these policies were relaxed.

According to the case data, approximately half of the total countrywide COVID-19 infections were caused by a single religious group. Furthermore, religion-related infection events were the leading cause of infections, followed by infections that occurred in medical facilities.

Based on patient data, it was found that infected patients, on average, took 5 days to get tested. Additionally, the data showed that the number of infections was significantly higher in people in their 20s. However, mortality predictions based on the data followed a different pattern. Although the overall mortality rate was 1.5%, a machine learning logistic regression model indicated that age, sex, and location of the patient could have an impact on the mortality rate. The statistical analysis revealed that male patients, older patients, and patients located in Daegu province were more likely to die from the virus.

Daegu province had the highest number of total infections due to the Shincheonji Church religious movement, which experienced an exceptional spread amongst its members. Unfortunately, members of the religious group also spread the infection to other cities and provinces. The higher mortality rate in this province may be attributed to the rapid rise in infection cases, which could have overwhelmed the medical care system, leading to suboptimal care for patients.

The fact that the largest group of infected patients is in their 20s, but the highest mortality is observed in older patients, is a cause for concern, particularly in environments such as religious practices and medical facilities that often have a multi-generational population. In such environments, the younger individuals who are less likely to develop severe symptoms can easily transmit the virus to the older and more vulnerable individuals who are at a higher risk of dying from the virus. This highlights the importance of taking appropriate measures to protect vulnerable populations, such as the elderly, in such environments to mitigate the risk of severe outcomes.

Based on tracking the number of contacts and patient age statistics, it has been found that patients in their 40s tend to infect the most people. While age groups tend to infect individuals within their own age range, it is also possible for parent-child relationships to contribute to the spread of the virus. It is important to consider such inter-generational transmission when implementing measures to control the spread of the virus, particularly in environments such as schools, where children and parents may come into close contact.

An important factor to consider in the context of the pandemic in South Korea is that schools were closed for midterm break when the pandemic started, and they were not reopened during this time. Given what we know about the spread of infections and inter-generational transmission, it is possible that this fortunate event may have helped to prevent a significant number of infections, especially parent-child infections. Had the schools been open as the pandemic began, there could have been a chain effect that spread to other age groups, increasing the overall number of infections in the country. The closure of schools during the initial outbreak period may have played a critical role in controlling the spread of the virus in South Korea.

Conclusions

Based on the result of the analysis I purpose the following guidelines:

  • Implement strict social distancing policies to control the spread of the virus, as demonstrated by the success of such policies in South Korea during the outbreak.

  • Make diagnostic kits available and begin testing procedures as soon as possible to minimize the risk of undiagnosed virus spread.

  • Focus on protecting vulnerable populations, such as the elderly, in multi-generational environments, such as religious practices and medical facilities, to mitigate the risk of severe outcomes. Where closure is unavailable strict testing and isolation policy must be implemented.

  • Consider online-schooling to limit the virus spread amongst the children causing inter-generational chain effects.

  • Ensure that adequate medical care is available to manage the rise in infection cases. Prepare procedures for inter-province medical capacity sharing in a case of an extreme outbreak in a single location.

  • Collect as much patient data as possible and use machine learning statistics for triage decisions in extremely dire situations.
